      "text": "I [https://moxie.org/2022/01/07/web3-first-impressions.html post] also wanted to create a more traditional NFT. Most people think of images and digital art when they think of NFTs, but NFTs generally do not store that data on-chain. For most NFTs of most images, that would be much too expensive.\n\nInstead of storing the data on-chain, NFTs instead contain a URL that points to the data. What surprised me about the standards was that there‚Äôs no hash commitment for the data located at the URL. Looking at many of the NFTs on popular marketplaces being sold for tens, hundreds, or millions of dollars, that URL often just points to some VPS running Apache somewhere. Anyone with access to that machine, anyone who buys that domain name in the future, or anyone who compromises that machine can change the image, title, description, etc for the NFT to whatever they‚Äôd like at any time (regardless of whether or not they ‚Äúown‚Äù the token). There‚Äôs nothing in the NFT spec that tells you what the image ‚Äúshould‚Äù be, or even allows you to confirm whether something is the ‚Äúcorrect‚Äù image."
